{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":13664,"record_hash":"sha256:28744251ec376615914bd24936559604dcde3d81c7cee38ae4f7724457ef0e23","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:01:42.352Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"Lets consider how this data might be accessed. I imagine a few use cases in the future.\n\n1. Session handoff\nA user prompts their coding agent on their laptop. No code has been writte. They wanna continue working on this session possibly on another machine and possibly with another agent. For example the work was started with Claude Code, but the user wants to continue working on a remote machine with openclaw (or vice versa - a user has prompted a bunch of stuff at their openclaw machine and wish to continue locally where they can test the code. For this use case to work we wanna be able to capture relevant context via git-meta, then use git as the transport and then finally on the other side, the other agent needs to be able to access this context in a way that makes sense to the agent. This use case assumes that both machines have a gitbutler CLI installed and they share a remote.\n\n2. Sharing session details with a colleague\nA user prompts their coding agent and after some iteration they produce code they are happy with and create pull request with it. It would be useful if the PR could include a link to a GitButler website where other team members can browse what happened in that session - the type of promps that were made, what questions the user and the agent discussed, how detailed was the prompting, what edge cases were considered etc. This would help others on the team understand how considerate was the code generation (i.e. carful planning and prompting vs \"pls fix\"). It can also be helpful in spreading knowledge within the team for what are good prompting patters. And even for this feature, a colleague may use the context to \"continue\" the conversation - lets say somebody submitted a PR and when checking the agentlog on the website link, I as the reviewer can simply ask as an example \"did you consider the payments in foreign currency edge case?\".\n\nNeither of these use cases 1 and 2 are something we want to implement now. However, I would like you to think about the data that we are storing and the access pattern that would be required for these 2 use cases. I imagine we would need to additionally store plan documents as well but that can come later. The most important question right now is to design a system where:\n- we store the right and relevant type of data\n- the data is stored in a way that is convinient for implementing our use cases\n\nOne interesting question is that of where the data is attached - at the root of the project or on a branch? Part of the problem with using branches is that they are ephemeral but there were some ideas around having generated ids that are durable and point to the relevant thing. But for now, the main task is to figure out the data shape i think. Also anything that I have not thought about yet?\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:01:42.352Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"Lets consider how this data might be accessed. I imagine a few use cases in the future.\n\n1. Session handoff\nA user prompts their coding agent on their laptop. No code has been writte. They wanna continue working on this session possibly on another machine and possibly with another agent. For example the work was started with Claude Code, but the user wants to continue working on a remote machine with openclaw (or vice versa - a user has prompted a bunch of stuff at their openclaw machine and wish to continue locally where they can test the code. For this use case to work we wanna be able to capture relevant context via git-meta, then use git as the transport and then finally on the other side, the other agent needs to be able to access this context in a way that makes sense to the agent. This use case assumes that both machines have a gitbutler CLI installed and they share a remote.\n\n2. Sharing session details with a colleague\nA user prompts their coding agent and after some iteration they produce code they are happy with and create pull request with it. It would be useful if the PR could include a link to a GitButler website where other team members can browse what happened in that session - the type of promps that were made, what questions the user and the agent discussed, how detailed was the prompting, what edge cases were considered etc. This would help others on the team understand how considerate was the code generation (i.e. carful planning and prompting vs \"pls fix\"). It can also be helpful in spreading knowledge within the team for what are good prompting patters. And even for this feature, a colleague may use the context to \"continue\" the conversation - lets say somebody submitted a PR and when checking the agentlog on the website link, I as the reviewer can simply ask as an example \"did you consider the payments in foreign currency edge case?\".\n\nNeither of these use cases 1 and 2 are something we want to implement now. However, I would like you to think about the data that we are storing and the access pattern that would be required for these 2 use cases. I imagine we would need to additionally store plan documents as well but that can come later. The most important question right now is to design a system where:\n- we store the right and relevant type of data\n- the data is stored in a way that is convinient for implementing our use cases\n\nOne interesting question is that of where the data is attached - at the root of the project or on a branch? Part of the problem with using branches is that they are ephemeral but there were some ideas around having generated ids that are durable and point to the relevant thing. But for now, the main task is to figure out the data shape i think. Also anything that I have not thought about yet?\n"}]}}}